FoodHub Project

Data Analysis By Okesola Moses Olusola

Problem Statement

Description

Context

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant.

The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer.

The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience.

Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

FoodHub Data Description

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary order_id: Unique ID of the order

customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food

restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant

cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer

cost: Cost of the order

day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)

rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5 food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food.

delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package.

# Get orders that cost above 20 dollars
FoodHub_data_greater_than_20 = FoodHub_data[FoodHub_data['cost_of_the_order'] > 20]
# Calculate the number of total orders where the cost is above 20 dollars
print('The number of total orders that cost above 20 dollars is:', FoodHub_data_greater_than_20.shape[0])

# Calculate the percentage of such orders in the dataset
percentage = (FoodHub_data_greater_than_20.shape[0] / FoodHub_data.shape[0]) * 100

print("Percentage of orders above 20 dollars:", round(percentage, 2), '%')

number_of_orders = top_customers.values

  • Some of the cuisine types have long whiskers while some have short whiskers. A few outliers are noticed.

  • Outliers are found in the cost of ordering Korean, Mediterranean, and Vietnamese cuisines.

  • The ordering of Korean, Japanese, Mexican, American, Indian, Italian, Mediterranean, Chinese, Middle Eastern, Southern, Vietnamese, and Spanish cuisines are left skewed.

  • Thai and French are right skewed.

The company wants to provide a promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants. The condition to get the offer is that the restaurants must have a rating count of more than 50 and the average rating should be greater than 4. Find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer. (Question 13)

In [104]:
# Filter the rated restaurants
FoodHub_data_rated = FoodHub_data[FoodHub_data['rating'] != 'Not given'].copy()

# Convert rating column from object to integer
FoodHub_data_rated['rating'] = FoodHub_data_rated['rating'].astype('int')

# Calculate rating count by grouping the data by 'restaurant_name' and counting the ratings
FoodHub_data_rated['rating_count'] = FoodHub_data_rated.groupby('restaurant_name')['rating'].transform('count')

# Calculate average rating by grouping the data by 'restaurant_name' and calculating the mean of ratings
FoodHub_data_rated['average_rating'] = FoodHub_data_rated.groupby('restaurant_name')['rating'].transform('mean')
# Filter the restaurants based on the criteria
filtered_restaurants = FoodHub_data_rated[(FoodHub_data_rated['rating_count'] > 50) & (FoodHub_data_rated['average_rating'] > 4)]

# Print the restaurant names
print(filtered_restaurants['restaurant_name'].unique())

The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders.(Question 14)

In [32]:
# Calculate the surcharges for each order
FoodHub_data['surcharge'] = 0
FoodHub_data.loc[FoodHub_data['cost_of_the_order'] > 20, 'surcharge'] = FoodHub_data['cost_of_the_order'] * 0.25
FoodHub_data.loc[(FoodHub_data['cost_of_the_order'] > 5) & (FoodHub_data['cost_of_the_order'] <= 20), 'surcharge'] = FoodHub_data['cost_of_the_order'] * 0.15

# Calculate the net revenue
Total_revenue = FoodHub_data['surcharge'].sum()

print("Total revenue generated by the company: $", Total_revenue)

Total revenue generated by the company: $ 6166.303

The company wants to analyze the total time required to deliver the food. What percentage of orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered from the time the order is placed? (The food has to be prepared and then delivered.) (Question 15)

In [106]:
# Calculate the total time required for each order (preparation time + delivery time)
FoodHub_data['total_time'] = FoodHub_data['food_preparation_time'] + FoodHub_data['delivery_time']

# Calculate the percentage of orders that take more than 60 minutes to get delivered
percentage = (FoodHub_data[FoodHub_data['total_time'] > 60].shape[0] / FoodHub_data.shape[0]) * 100

# Print the percentage
print("Percentage of orders taking more than 60 minutes for delivery:", round(percentage, 2), "%")

Percentage of orders taking more than 60 minutes for delivery: 10.54 %

Conclusions and Recommendations

Cuisine Type:

1.American cuisine has the highest number of orders, while
Vietnamese cuisine has the lowest. 2.The distribution of cuisine types is symmetric, with noticeable symmetry in Japanese, Mexican, American, Indian, and Italian cuisines. 3.There are a few outliers in the distribution of cuisine types.

Cost of the Order:

1.The cost of the order is highest at slightly above 12.1 dollars and lowest at slightly above 19.5 dollars. 2.The distribution of the cost of the order is right-skewed. The minimum cost of the order is 5 dollars, and the maximum is 35 dollars. 3.The median cost of the order is slightly above 14 dollars.

Day of the Week:

1.The demand for cuisine food is higher during weekends than weekdays. 2.There are over 1350 orders during weekends compared to slightly above 545 orders on weekdays. 3.The total number of orders during weekends is about three times the total on weekdays.

Rating:

1.'Not given' rating accounts for about 39% of the ratings and occurs most frequently. 2.Ratings 5, 4, and 3 account for about 31%, 20%, and 10% of the total ratings, respectively. 3.The rating distribution is symmetric, with the median occurring at rating 5.

Food Preparation Time:

1.The count of food preparation time is highest at about 21 minutes. 2.The least count of cuisine orders occurs at about 29 minutes. 3.The distribution of food preparation time is symmetric. 4.The median food preparation time is 27 minutes. 5.The minimum food preparation time is 20 minutes, and the maximum is 35 minutes. 6.The distribution of food preparation time is right-skewed.

Delivery Time:

1.Delivery time increases in count between 22.5 and 25 minutes, with 24 minutes having the highest count. 2.The minimum number of cuisines is delivered between 30.4 and 31.4 minutes. 3.Delivery time of about 31 minutes has the lowest occurrence or count. 4.The highest number of cuisines is delivered between 24 and 30 minutes. 6.Delivery time is left-skewed. 7.The minimum delivery time is 15 minutes, and the maximum is 32.5 minutes. 8.The median delivery time is 25 minutes. 9.The 25th percentile of the delivery time distribution is 20 minutes, and the 75th percentile is slightly higher than 28 minutes.

Relationships:

1.There is a weak negative correlation (-0.03) between the cost of the order and delivery time. 2.There is a weak positive relationship (0.01) between food preparation time and delivery time. 3.There is a weak positive correlation (0.04) between food preparation time and the cost of the order.

Based on these conclusions, the following recommendations can be made:

1.Focus on promoting American cuisine to maintain its high number of orders.

2.Consider strategies to increase the popularity and demand for Vietnamese cuisine.

3.Monitor and manage outliers in the distribution of cuisine types.

4.Analyze the factors contributing to the higher demand for cuisine food during weekends and leverage this information for marketing and operations.

5.Pay attention to customer ratings and strive to improve the overall rating by addressing any issues or concerns. 6.Optimize food preparation time to ensure consistency and efficiency.

7.Streamline delivery processes to minimize delivery time and improve customer satisfaction.

8.Monitor the relationship between the cost of the order, food preparation time, and delivery time to identify any potential areas for improvement or cost optimization.

9.Identify the cuisine types that consistently receive high ratings across both weekends and weekdays. These popular cuisine types can be the focus of marketing efforts and menu planning.

10.Based on the analysis of ratings and customer preferences, consider offering specials or promotions for popular cuisine types during specific time slots or days. This can help attract more customers and increase sales during those periods.

11 Continuously gather feedback from customers regarding their experience with delivery time, preparation time, and the quality of different cuisine types. Use this feedback to make improvements and address any issues that arise.

12.Continuously monitor the impact of your efforts on the business metrics, such as customer satisfaction, ratings, and sales. Make adjustments as needed based on the feedback and data you collect.

13.Regularly review and update company's approach of data analysis to ensure that customer expectations are met and improving the overall food business.
